This is primarily a "which is better to use" question.

The guy who first showed me TF and gave me sample .tf files to 
look at used sockmload for all his worlds.  For those that
aren't familiar with it, "/sockmload on" means that whenever a
world is /fg'ed, it loads the file associated with it when the
world was defined.

By the sockmload method, each world has a file associated with
it that first /purges when that world is switched to, then
loads all files and stuff for that world.  Obviously all that
loading and purging isn't totally efficient, but it works fine.

After lurking in this group for a while, I get the impression
that most of you don't use this feature, but use WORLD hooks
instead.  Also, /help sockmload specifically says "the WORLD
hook is more useful than sockmload").

Well if its more useful and the standard I certainly want to
know more about it... I understand how hooks work, but I'm not
sure what the best way to convert my existing files is, or how
exactly you all do things normally.

What do you normally do about commands that have the same name
but totally different functions in different worlds?  And what
about commands that you really only want defined in certain
worlds?  Do y'all just have a whole lot of WORLD hooks?  Or
what?  Or is this not something most of you deal with?  I often
use one instance of TF to connect to several worlds, so this
is important for me.

