I fear the world hook won't do it for you.

You already mentioned the point where it fails, I'll describe it with one
example. In world "Ramona" I play Ramona, a cleric who can cast a 'create
food' spell. So whenever she's hungry, she just grows a mushroom and eats
it. I defined the command /eat to exactly do that.
Now in world "Ayla" I play a thief. She does not know any magic, so she has
to take a bread (or whatever she has as food) out of her backpack and eat
it. For me as player it's the same action, eating, so I want to define this
macro to be called /eat too. But this would overwrite the macro from world
Ramona (even with -w switch).

There's one workaround if you have only few such macros. You can put in an
/if switch checking for the actual world and from this choosing what to do.
But it's ugly especially if you have to update them all for every change and
every new world ... (If you need an example for that, I can post it.)

The point of macros which are only defined in one world is no problem.
/def -w<world> ... will do the trick.

So, if you only have very few diffently implemented macros (like the
Ramona/Ayla example), using /def -w (and with this, the switching of macros
by the world hook) would be possible. Else stick to /sockmload on I'd say.

