> > macro to be called /eat too. But this would overwrite the macro from world
> > Ramona (even with -w switch).

Redefining /eat with sockmload is okay if you never execute /eat for a
background world.  But what if you want to to make a trigger in each
world that calls /eat when the world says you're hungry?

First, you wouldn't want the trigger to be redefined every time you switched
foreground worlds, because you want to detect hunger in a world even if that
world is backgrounded.  So you need to have all the triggers defined all
the time (or at least when the corresponding worlds are connected), using
the -w option.  e.g.

  /def -wfoo -t'You feel hungry.' foo_hungry = /eat
  /def -wbar -t'Your stomach grumbles.' bar_hungry = /eat

Second, you need to have a different version of /eat for each world.
As others have suggested, this can be done by writing an /eat "wrapper"
that calls another macro based on the world name:

  /def eat = /${world_name}_eat %*

Putting this all together:

  Put these commands in your .tfrc or some other global file:
    /addworld foo ... foo.tf
    /addworld bar ... bar.tf
    /def eat = /${world_name}_eat %*

  File foo.tf:
    /def foo_eat = eat %*
    /def -wfoo -t'You feel hungry.' foo_hungry = /eat

  File bar.tf:
    /def bar_eat = feed me %*
    /def -wbar -t'Your stomach grumbles.' bar_hungry = /eat


...with sockmload=off, because the world-specific versions are never deleted,
so they only need to be loaded when you first connect.

Granted, /foo_hungry could call /foo_eat directly, instead of going through
/eat.  But you still want /eat for manual calls, which was how this whole
thing started.



None of that has anything to do with WORLD hooks, because it was written
such that nothing needed to be done when changing the foreground world.
But in cases where you do need something executed when you bring a world
to the foreground, those commands are often different than (or a subset
of) the commands you want executed when you first connect.  In those
cases, it's usually better to have a WORLD hook execute those commands,
instead of reloading everything with sockmload.

Sockmload is okay for simple things, but it's not very flexible.  To
get more sophisticated, you usually have to use techniques like WORLD
hooks, /def -w, and wrapper macros with ${world_name}.

