You can make use of the idle(world) function.

Also, your most recent version only generates the @pemit when the
trigger runs, so it'll only @pemit at the first activity after 5 minutes
of idle.  Rather than emitting immediately the first 5 minutes of idle.

Although, personally, I think your version is more useful.  (if you
replace @pemit with /echo so things go in the right order).  Since when
you get a line after an X minute pause, you'd see the starting time for
the next batch of text, rather than the requested version which shows
an approximate end time of the previous batch.


You might not want to call the command tick, since there is a tick.tf in 
the distribution which defines /tick.


Instead of checking every 15 seconds, we try to check only as often as
something could change.  So when things are slow, we only check once per 
5 minutes.

Once the keyboard has gone idle 5 minutes, we check all the worlds.  If
any of them have been idle 5 minutes and we haven't already sent the
pemit, we send the pemit, we mark that we sent it, and we install a
one-shot world specific trigger which will clear our `sent it' flag
once activity resumes.


;; timeout in seconds
/set idle_pemit_time=300

/def idle_pemit =\
    /kill %{idle_pemit_pid}%;\
    /if (idle() < idle_pemit_time) \
	/let max_idle=$[idle()]%;\
    /else \
	/let max_idle=0%;\
	/_idle_pemit $(/listsockets -s)%;\
    /endif%;\
    /let next_time=$[idle_pemit_time - max_idle + 1]%;\
    /if (next_time < 15) \
	/let next_time=15%;\
    /endif%;\
    /repeat -%{next_time} 1 /idle_pemit%;\
    /set idle_pemit_pid=%?


/def _idle_pemit =\
    /let idle=%;\
    /let already_sent=%;\
    /while ({#}) \
	/let world=%{1}%;\
	/test idle := idle(world)%;\
	/test already_sent := idle_pemit_sent_%{world}%;\
	/if (idle < idle_pemit_time) \
	    /test max_idle := (idle > max_idle ? idle : max_idle)%;\
	/elseif (!already_sent) \
	    /def -1 -w%{world} -F -p%{maxpri} -mglob -t'*' -q idle_pemit_%{world} =\
		/unset idle_pemit_sent_%{world}%;\
	    /set idle_pemit_sent_%{world}=1%;\
	    /let fmt=\%a \%b \%d \%H:\%M:\%S \%Y%;\
	    /send -w%{world} @pemit .................. $[ftime(fmt, time())]%;\
	/endif%;\
	/shift%;\
    /done

/idle_pemit

