Well, actually idle(world) is completely useless since it only measures
from received lines not sent lines.

Suggestions:

1. Send hook to keep track of last time you sent something.
   Disadvantages: your bot might set it off, only measures `sending to
   mud'.  Advantages: easy to have world specific idle times.

2. Rebind ^J to keep track of last time you typed that.  Disadvantages:
   only measures `pressing return' (can't tell local command from
   sending to mud), have to guess using fg_world() for world specific
   idle times (but usually it's right).  Advantages: bot responses don't
   have to use `/send' to avoid setting off send hooks, you could do
   this to a bunch of other bindings too.

3. Rebind TAB to keep track of last time TAB used, make a my_idle()
   macro which compares idle() and the delta from the TAB time.  If
   delta <= idle(), then it was a TAB.  Disadvantages: not world
   specific, tricky (but not impossible) to figure out "real" idle time
   when there has been a TAB.  Advantages: measures all typing
   except TAB, you could do this to other bindings too.

4. You can't use /recall -i 1, since tf will update the timestamp on
   "current" line before the macro is run.  This makes it mostly the
   same as idle().


I'd probably pick 2 as the most useful, since you probably aren't
"active" unless you've recently typed something.

The downside is that unless you use `/bg' doing things like `/expr
500+3' to balance your checkbook will count against your "idle" time on
that world.  Course you could work around that by just not reseting the
time if the input buffer started with with a `/'.  But then that
wouldn't count when you ran your `/eat' macro which did send something
to the mud.

