Hi,

thanks to all who helped me with this problem. Still any ideas are welcome,
here's what I am using now.

(To all who don't remember or who misunderstood me: I wanted to have a
function similar to the builtin idle(), but which does NOT count the
tabulator key as a sign I became active again. If called with an argument,
it does not, like the builtin idle(<world>) return the time since when there
has not been any activity in this world, but instead the time since when 
I have not been active in this world.)

;;; initialize the variable which saves when I pressed <return> last time:
/set _<wordname>LastNewlineTime=$[time()]

;;; set this variable again at each press of <return>:
/def -b'^J' b_Newline1 = \
    /set _${world_name}LastNewlineTime=$[time()] %; /dokey NEWLINE
/def -b'^M' b_Newline2 = \
    /set _${world_name}LastNewlineTime=$[time()] %; /dokey NEWLINE

;;; compute the time since last time when I pressed the <return> button:
/def myidle = \
    /let time=$[time()]%;\
    /let world=${world_name}%;\
    /if ({#}=1) /let world=%{1}%; /endif %;\
    /return $(/eval /echo - $$[{time}-{_%{world}LastNewlineTime}])
 
Btw, while testing this I found something which looks like a bug
in /return:
I first had a construction /if ... /return ... %; /else /return ... %; /endif
which always gave back the value of the comparision in the if statement and
not the value computed in /return ... !


