I've noticed that a lot of the macros posted recently (by many people)
are using `/eval' when it is not needed, in multiple places.  And
someday it's going to cause you problems.

> ;;; initialize the variable which saves when I pressed <return> last time:
> /set _<wordname>LastNewlineTime=$[time()]
> 
> ;;; set this variable again at each press of <return>:
> /def -b'^J' b_Newline1 = \
>     /set _${world_name}LastNewlineTime=$[time()] %; /dokey NEWLINE
> /def -b'^M' b_Newline2 = \
>     /set _${world_name}LastNewlineTime=$[time()] %; /dokey NEWLINE

I'd stick the time setting in another macro like `/reset_idle', and call 
that from the ^J ^M bindings.  AND, you most likely want a CONNECT hook
which also does the reset on that world.  Otherwise when you first
connect to a world, but haven't typed anything to it yet, you'd be
considered idle for ~28 years.

> ;;; compute the time since last time when I pressed the <return> button:
> /def myidle = \
>     /let time=$[time()]%;\
>     /let world=${world_name}%;\
>     /if ({#}=1) /let world=%{1}%; /endif %;\
>     /return $(/eval /echo - $$[{time}-{_%{world}LastNewlineTime}])

/def myidle =\
    /return time() - _%{1-${world_name}}LastNewlineTime


> Btw, while testing this I found something which looks like a bug
> in /return:
> I first had a construction /if ... /return ... %; /else /return ... %; /endif
> which always gave back the value of the comparision in the if statement and
> not the value computed in /return ... !

There are a bunch of quirky bugs with /return and if/else statements,
also a few really neat ones involving /while when you're in a nested
macro call where the parent macro is in an if clause.  I think they've
been fixed for 40a5, but the best thing to do when you find a bug like
this is make a very small reproducable version of it, and send it in.

For example, your description above sounds like the following should
return 1 not `a':

/def foo =\
    /if (1) \
	/return "a"%;\
    /else \
	/return "b"%;\
    /endif

But it doesn't.  It works as expected in 40a4.  When it's not clear from
the description of the bug how to reproduce it, it's harder to fix it.
So the problem you saw has probably been fixed in a5, but without being
able to test your specific example, who knows.


For comparison, macros which set off a /return & nested /while bug.


/def tf_bug = \
    /if (1) \
        /tf_bug_%;\
    /endif


/def tf_bug_ =\
    /return 0%;\
    /while (1) \
    /done%;\
    /echo -e -ah BUG

