That is exactly what it does.  Note you have to call it in expression
macro-as-function syntax:

/expr myidle()           --> 10
/expr myidle("druid")    --> 5
/expr myidle(fg_world()) --> 0

/def -mregexp -t'yams' yams =\
    /if (myidle() >= 300 & bot_mode) \
	/send say ROOF!%;\
    /endif




Now how does it work:

One of the two things being used here are the fact that /return takes an
expression (ie same as /test), so we can just say things like `/return
time() - last_time' and have the correct value returned.

The other is how %-substitution works.  %{VAR} substitutes the value of
VAR.  But %{VAR-default} uses VAR if the value is non-empty otherwise it 
uses the default.  So `%{1-${world_name}}' means if %{1} is non-empty
use the first argument, otherwise use the current world name.

Well, I guess the third thing being used here is that because /return
isn't a special form (ie, not /if or /while) a level of substitution
completes before return is called.  So
`/return time() - _%{1-$world_name}}LastNewlineTime' gets treated like:
call `return' with arguments `time() - _worldXLastNewlineTime'.  Then 
this is exactly of the form in the first paragraph above, so it returns
the appropriate value.



