Why this is potentially confusing:
1. tf has two extremely different "kinds" of operation: normal macro
   expansion and expression.
2. if & while are special forms so do normal macro expansion slightly
   differently than "normal".
3. There are two different ways of using if & while which behave
   somewhat differently: `/if () ...' and `/if <commands> /then'.


It's good to think about what tf does as it tries to execute each line
of a macro.

In general, tf first goes through and substitutes all of the various
%{var}, $[expr] and $(/command) in a _textual_ manner to the end of the
command, then "executes" the real command.  The first half of this two
step process is called substitution (/help substitution).

However, there are 2 "special forms" which don't under go the same kind
of complete substitution before tf does more work on them.  Those are
`if' and `while'.  And the reason it can't do this is because it can't
know which parts are supposed to be executed or not that early.  So,
with `if' and `while' tf checks a condition and then begins doing the
same kind of normal substitution & execution on the lines of the
bodies.  This part probably isn't too confusing, since you do tend to
expect that if you have:

/if /mytest /then \
    /echo $(/foo A)%;\
/else \
    /echo $(/foo B)%:\
/endif

that `/foo' should only be called once with either A or B.



