Susan Dittmar <dittmar@ph-cip.Uni-Koeln.DE> writes:
> does anyone know how to suppress the reset of the idle() time on a tab key
> press?

If idle() were conditional like that, it would lose some of its usefulness,
and become more confusing.

On Thu, 22 Jan 1998, Karen Etheridge wrote:
> Why not look at a different statistic, instead of idle()?  It sounds like you
> want your robots to work only if you are unidle _in that world_, not in TF
> in general.
> 
> So, why not take a look at the last time you sent something to that world?
> Or the last time you entered a command into TF?

David Moore wrote:
> Suggestions:
> 
> 1. Send hook to keep track of last time you sent something.
>    Disadvantages: your bot might set it off, only measures `sending to
>    mud'.  Advantages: easy to have world specific idle times.

To avoid having your bot set it off, you can
A. Have your bot always use /send, instead of implicit sends; or
B. Have your SEND hook reset the last_active_time only if (idle()==0), i.e.
   there was an implicit send and a key was just pressed.  (It's an imperfect
   hack: it can be tricked if your bot does an implicit send within 1 second
   of you pressing (for example) TAB.)

> 2. Rebind ^J to keep track of last time you typed that.  Disadvantages:
>    only measures `pressing return' (can't tell local command from
>    sending to mud), have to guess using fg_world() for world specific
>    idle times (but usually it's right).  Advantages: bot responses don't
>    have to use `/send' to avoid setting off send hooks, you could do
>    this to a bunch of other bindings too.

Or combine #1 and #2.  Bind ^J to /set last_return_time=$[time()], and have
a SEND hook reset last_active_time only if (last_return_time==time()), i.e.
there was an implicit send and RETURN was just pressed.  This eliminates
most of the problems with both methods.

> 3. Rebind TAB to keep track of last time TAB used, make a my_idle()
>    macro which compares idle() and the delta from the TAB time.  If
>    delta <= idle(), then it was a TAB.  Disadvantages: not world
>    specific, tricky (but not impossible) to figure out "real" idle time
>    when there has been a TAB.  Advantages: measures all typing
>    except TAB, you could do this to other bindings too.

But other keys typed within the same 1-second interval as the TAB will
be ignored.  That's no good.

> 4. You can't use /recall -i 1, since tf will update the timestamp on
>    "current" line before the macro is run.  This makes it mostly the
>    same as idle().

If you use $(/recall -it /1 [^/]*) (with an appropriate %time_format),
you get the last real non-blank input line that didn't start with "/".

