"Eliseo d'Annunzio, Esq." <sherlock@progsoc.uts.edu.au> writes:

> Anyone have a macro which would  take the following syntax:
> 
> /plus <variable> n1 n2 n3 n4 n5... ...nn
> 
> allowing n to be numeric or variable? I was thinking that an
> implementation of a recursive shift would do wonders in this case...
> 
> Could similar macros be made for say /minus (recursive subtraction),
> /times (recursive multiplication) and /div (recursive division?)... Anyone
> have any good ideas how we can bring such macros about?

/def plus =\
    /let result=0%;\
    /while ({#}) \
	/test result := result + %{1}%;\
	/shift%;\
    /done%;\
    /echo %{result}


Note that I use `%{1}' not `{1}' this allows you to use variable names
in the call, rather than just numbers.

If you want an expression version, so you can say:
/if (plus(a,b,c,d,10) > 5) ...

Then use `{1}' instead of `%{1}' and change the echo to a return.

