Gossamer wrote:
> Trouble is, my up-arrow and control-up-arrow BOTH show up 
> as ^[[A when I type 'em :(

Yep, on most systems, there's no difference between 'up' and 'ctrl-up'.
You can however use the keypad keys in application or keypad mode
(they send different codes in either mode).
Note: This only works for the keypad keys, not for the extra arrow keys.

For this purpose, my .tfrc has the following commands.
(This is just a small part of it, I bind _many_ more keys).

;; application mode (default on most systems)
/def -i -b^[[A Up   = /dokey recallb
/def -i -b^[[B Down = /dokey recallf
/def -i -b^[OA = /Up
/def -i -b^[OB = /Down

;; keypad numeric mode (default on some systems)
/def -i -b^[Ox Num8 = north
/def -i -b^[Or Num2 = south

;; Toggle keypad numeric / application mode (works on some systems)
;; Other systems have a standard key(combination) to toggle the modus
;; On X systems, you can use xterm*appkeypadDefault: True/False
/def -i keypad = \
	/toggle keypad%;\
	/if (keypad) /echo -r \033>%;/else /echo -r \033=%;/endif


Johan

