/def -i split =\
    /let opt_d==%;\
    /if (!getopts("d:")) /break%;/endif%;\
    /let opt_d=$(/escape ^] %{opt_d})%;\
    /let pat=^([^%{opt_d}]*[^ %{opt_d}])? *[%{opt_d}]? *(.*)%;\
    /@test regmatch(pat, {*})

Of course this only works for single character delimiters.  Well you
could say -d'=:' and it'd stop at the first of = or :, etc.

The key here is to quote the ^ and ] which are meaningful inside []
forms.  And instead of quoting all of ^$|()[].*?+ I just put a [] around 
the central opt_d.  You could also just quote all of those characters.

