The TIME column is the cpu usage time accumulated over the life of the
process.  It grows over time.  Probably the most useful way to look at it
is to divide it by the amount of time the process has been running, and
compare it to the cpu_time/real_time quotient of other processes.
Accumulating 4:00 in 2 hours sounds like a lot to me, but I can't say
for sure without comparing it to other processes on your machine.

Next time, post the output of "ps u".  In addition to accumulated time (TIME),
it shows the start time (START) and percentage of cpu time allocated to the
process in the last time slice (%CPU).  For detecting how much cpu a process
is eating _right_ _now_, %CPU is more useful than TIME.  If your tf is not
supposed to be doing anything, and its %CPU is high, you have a problem.

