One useful feature in zmud, one that a primary building block of bots and
such built in it, is trigger classes. What they do is allow a set of
triggers registered under class X to be simultaneously turned on and off as
needed, by using #T+ X and #T- X. I don't like zmud though but think it
would be neat to emulate such a feature in tf. I have a couple ideas about
how to do this and wanted to know what you guys think, and if anyone would
be interested in such a library.

One possibility is to use world_type to contain class info (assuming regexp
is default), eg:

/ADDWORLD -T"diku.myworld.autoassist.autocleric" ....

this would turn on diku autologin for one, and turn on the classes myworld,
autoassist and autocleric. You could then make libraries that would work in
different worlds and encapsulate your code better.

Defining triggers for such classes would then be very simple:

/def -T"autoassist" ...

would make a trigger in class autoassist.

You could even have triggers that require multiple classes to be enabled, etc.

But one problem remains is how to turn classes on and off when running
(which would be important for porting zmud scripts).

Making a set of functions to manipulate a comma separated string of words,
removing words, adding, etc would not be difficult, but how to change
world_type at runtime? Using /set world_type would work, but would probably
be very very bad and ugly. Would storing all info in an /ADDWORLD
definition, then rebuilding it to redefine a world at runtime be feasible?
Would that automatically update world_type at runtime for a world?

Another possibility is to build such a library using Susan's lists lib, and
have lists be classes containing names of trigger macros. Eg:

/def ... mytrig ...
/Tregister -c"autoassist" mytrig

Would that be more feasible?

Thanks in advance for any help.


