> Is it possible to have a trigger/macro which is triggered in all worlds
> except one (or named worlds)?

You have two options: use -T, after carefully defining world types:

define all the other worlds to be type "foo", and the other world to be
type "bar", and use -Tfoo in your /def
(You can also use glob or regexp matching on your -T option, depending on
which -m option you pick, or the value of %{matching}, if you choose your
type names so that you match on a pattern, but that's probably more than
you need for something like this)

or,

/def <options here> macro_name = \
  /if ({$world_name} =~ "name of world you don't want to run in") \
    /break %; /endif %;\
  <body of macro/trigger here>

You will still get a "trigger in world <foo>" message though, if you didn't
use the -q flag in the /def.  (And the text will still highlight, if you
used -a or -P.)


