> +++ /set Splutty_GREATER_LASTED=887383647

The /return is not skipped; you can see it in your mecho output (after the
expansion of your /do_echo macro).  The thing is, /eval is creating an
extra macro evaluation level (as you can see from the number of '+'s), and
/return is returning from that level, not the level of /calc_prot_falling.
In the mecho output, you can see it execute the /return at +++ level, skip
the rest of the /eval body (i.e.  the /endif) that would normally occur at
the +++ level, and resume at the ++ level above it.

Your use of %%; and %; is consistent with your use of /eval, but your
use of /eval is the problem.  You should either wrap the whole body
in /eval:

  /def calc_prot_falling = \
      /eval \
          /if (%{2}_%{1}_TIME =~ "") \
              /do_echo %{1} on %{2} is DOWN in <unknown> sec.%%;\
              /return 0%%;\
          /endif%%;\
          /set %{2}_%{1}_LASTED=$$[time()-%{2}_%{1}_TIME]%%;\
          ...

or use /test in the /if, since it causes the extra evaluation you need
in the condition:

  /def calc_prot_falling = \
      /if /test %{2}_%{1}_TIME =~ ""%; /then \
          /do_echo %{1} on %{2} is DOWN in <unknown> sec.%;\
          /return 0%;\
      /endif%;\
      /eval /set %{2}_%{1}_LASTED=$$[time()-%{2}_%{1}_TIME]%;\
      ...

In the latter case, I might also use /test to set the LASTED variable,
and avoid /eval altogether:

      /test %{2}_%{1}_LASTED := time() - %{2}_%{1}_TIME%;\

