Yes, that's a little unclear.  An /eval is basically the same as a macro 
execution, which is why it has some other strange effects (other than
the earlier discussed substitution problems).  Think of

/A%;\
/eval STUFF%;\
/B

as

/A%;\
/def temp_macro = STUFF%;\
/temp_macro %*%;\
/undef temp_macro%;\
/B

Ie, when you're in a /eval, it's basically like an unnamed macro with
the same args as you had.  So /return returns from the /eval, not the
macro.


