> What can't we handle? Use high priority fall through def's..

1.  If you log the global output (ie /log ~/foo), it stores lines as
they come to the foreground, not as they arrive.

2.  You need to store lines like `---- World cave ----' in a global log, 
and /recall output, etc.

3.  The more general case of this is that you need to store output sent
to worlds via all sorts of means, such as /echo -wfoo.  This is often
done even to non-connected worlds.  You can't just wrap /echo, since
the echo() function and builtin output should be recorded also.

4.  Currently lines are recorded to the log file after all
triggers/highlights/etc are run on it.  A high priority trigger reverses 
this and may change the behaviour of some macros.  Various people turn
on logging automatically via trigger, and this would break things for
them.

5.  If you try to work around problem 4 by delayed operation, and using
/recall to figure out what to log, you will miss lines that are -aG.
And it still doesn't fix all of problem 2.  Number 3 would still cause
problems since you'd have to keep scanning background worlds, and you
couldn't do it fast enough not to break certain macros (although you
could override /quote, /sys, /sh, etc to help lower the chances of
breaking them).


