The issue is not that the match type is regexp, but how complicated it
is.  With regular expressions you can have very complicated patterns,
which are very loose at the beginning (eg. starting with .*) and very
complicated at the end, which can lead to O(n^2) time doubling back to
the beginning of the regular expression, as each test string matches or
doesn't match at the end.

> /def -p2 -aBCblue -t'{*} multipages*' hilite_mpage2
> /def -p2 -aBCblue -t'{*} multi-pages*' hilite_mpage3
> 
> I replaced them with:
> 
> /def -p2 -aBCblue -mregexp -t"(multipages|multi-pages)" hilite_mpage
> 
> Would the two global matches still be faster and more efficient than one
> regexp match?

The only difference you've got between these two is that the first (glob
matching is short for globular, not global) is not case-sensitive,
and will only allow one word between the multi word.  If you want a
regexp that's closer to the glob, use:

-t'^[^ ]+ (multipages|multi-pages)'

and you can simplify this to  -t'^[^ ]+ multi-?pages'

> I started with this:
> /def -w'ss' -p1 -abCgreen -t'* the scanner light shows green*' scanner_green
> /def -w'ss' -p1 -abCgreen -t'* the autopilot light shows green*'
> scanner_green2
> 
> I ended up with this: 
> /def -i -w'ss' -p2 -abCgreen -mregexp -t"(scanner light shows
> green|autopilot light shows green)" scanner_green
> 
> Am I actually slowing TF down by doing this matching? I assumed 1 regexp
> match would end up being more efficient than 2 global matches...

No, you are slowing TF down by just a tiny wee bit with these regexps, as
they are simple and don't have lots of .* and parentheses (multiple possible
paths, each of which must be tested).

Again, you can simplify down to  -t'the (scanner|autopilot) light shows green'

As you write a trigger, generally it's pretty cut and dried which matching
style you have to use.  If you can get away with the simplicity of globs,
and case-insensitivity is okay, always go for the glob.  Likewise, if you
can use -msimple, use that when you can too.

As an example of some more complicated, multipath regexps:

  -t'^([Gg]ive me a )?([Qq]uot(e( for| by| from)?|ing)|\
  [Tt]idbit for|([Dd]irt|[Ss]cuttlebutt) (on|for)|[Ss]lag) ([^ ]+)$' 

  -t'^[Hh]ow (many|much)( [\'"]?(.*[^\'"])[\'"]?)? \
  (quotes|tidbits|scuttlebutt|hearsay|dirts?)\
  ( do you (have|know)|have you (got|heard))?\
  ( matching [\'"]?(.*[^\'"])[\'"]?)?$' \

These are complicated enough that they must go through a first pass via
a -t'*' trigger, to strip out the '^[^ ]+ says,? \"(.*)\"' things first,
before being /trigger -w into the world where the patterns above are
defined.  If you didn't understand what I just said, don't worry. :)
The multiple paths are just done for the sake of creating more tirgger
combinations, and for getting the benefit of more than the allowed 9
parentheses per pattern.



