Here's my experience of compiling tf version 4.0 alpha 4 under gnuwin32
beta 19 on windows 95, using the updated for b19 coolviews .dll (which
should have nothing to do with compiling but just mentioning it). I have no
mount table what so ever, and have no idea how it should affect or
shouldn't affect compilation.

I changed unix/Config to install in /usr/local... set make to make --unix
just in case (yes I tried it both ways, and yes I used cygnus.bat to set
the environment) set term to hardcore vt220 and tfconfig ran like a champ,
but when I got to the make part things started not going so well. At first
I tried to change unix/Config and even unix/tfconfig around but that turned
out not to be the problem.

Whenever unixmake got to the actual make part, it would spit out:

make: *** wait: Invalid argument.  Stop.

I then went to src and tried running just "make".

At first, it it spit out the same error, then it started making a file or
two, and then spitting that error out again.

I got bored of typing make all the time and wanted to see what would happen
so I made a little script and ran it in the src dir:

temp.sh:
------------------------
make
while [ $? != 0 ]; do \
  make;\
done
------------------------

Make kept chugging on and barfing out the same error here and there, I
think there was only one compilation warning though.

It compiled and linked everything, kept spitting out errors in the
postinstall part and then I saw, understandably, alot of waiting for
unfinished jobs messages. This is where my boneheaded script kept looping
through the making library part.

I got the above mentioned error on the:

        @echo '## Creating links so old library names still work...'

line.

I figured I got through every dependency but the libraries one, so I copied
the remaining commands (the rm -f ... ln -s ... ; \ lines) after this line
in this dependancy to /usr/local/lib/tf... and ran it.

Figuring I was done, it was time to try running tf.

After realizing that tf-40a4 didn't have an .exe prefix for some reason. I
did:

mv tf-40a4 tf-40a4.exe
rm tf.exe
ln -s tf-40a4.exe tf.exe

doing an unset TFLIBDIR so that it would load the library files from the
new directory I finally ran it and to my immediate joy saw the familiar
errors and warnings from my various .tf concoctions -)

Now it connected to my world just fine and ran. Visual mode didn't quite
work but I would expect that from the terminal setting I used. Also,
whenver I tried to start it as tf -n then /world to something I would get:

main_loop: select

and it would exit.

Another problem I noticed, again probably related to my terminal setting is
that when instead of using a command window I try to telnet into my machine
I get no keyboard input while in tf. The only thing that seems to respond
is ctrl+c and that resumes immediately (using the right terminal and keymap
settings of course). I'll try to rebuild it with ncurses and see if that
helps...

My gut feeling tells me the make errors come from b19 using bash2... But I
could be wrong. If anyone has compiled tf with bash2.something as /bin/sh
lemme know.

That's all, sorry for rambling.
