""' line at all. This is no big problem. But I can't understand why should
we use (.*[^\"]) instead of ([^\"]*). Unless ofcourse the string has many
'"' marks in it. In which case your regexp matches 'tells you "wonder"boy"
hood"' but not 'tells you "wonder"boy""'. And again, unless this is the
point, I can't see why we shouldn't use (.*). This works even if the
string is not anchored at the end, because expression matching is greedy
by default. So, I would use,

-t'tells you \"([^\"]*)\"$'

if I want it NOT to match multiple quotes in the tell, or,

-t'tells you \"(.*)\"$'

if I want them to be matched or don't care.

