This is off topic, but it seems like a concern of several folks,
so what the heck.

Pine allows you have multiple "inboxes" which it will check 
automatically for new mail by pressing the <TAB> key.  You
can also set it to automatically put read mail into a different
folder--and you can set a "read" folder for *each* inbox.

So far I have 16 inboxes.  If I get added to a new list, I will
add another inbox.  Some of these have >1000 mails, and it's 
still fast.

.pinerc options to look at:
# List of incoming msg folders besides INBOX, e.g. ={host2}inbox, {host3}inbox
# Syntax: optnl-label {optnl-imap-host-name}folder-path
incoming-folders="mbox" /users/nmiller/mail/mbox,
        "wakeup" ~/mail/wakeup,
        "admin" ~/mail/admin,
[etc]

# List of folder pairs; the first indicates a folder to archive, and the
# second indicates the folder read messages in the first should
# be moved to.
incoming-archive-folders=mbox mbox.read,
			 wakeup, wakeup.read

Turn on the feature "auto-move-read-messages" if you want the
moves to happen automatically.

Pine's help is very extensive, there are a lot of features to it.

