>The last one, of course. This can all be caught using a single trigger.

Not necessarily faster. The issue is not so simple.

We have 3 simple options on how to do this

First:
/def -t"You punch *" = blah
/def -t"You hit *"   = blah
/def -t"You miss *"  = blah
/def -t"You slash *" = blah

This is fairly fast, because 4 different glob matches hardly slow the
client down.

Second:
/def -t"You *" = (lots of ifs etc.)

This is probably not as fast, as we still have to match the You
punch/hit/miss/slash lines from the previous ones and we end up with 5
comparisons instead of 4. Ofcourse we can look directly at the second word
of the matched part, but I doubt if it still gets faster than the first one.

Third:
/def -mregexp -t"^You (punch|hit|miss|slash) " = blah

This uses a regexp match instead of glob matches, but is fairly fast still
because the regexp engine is very efficient and it will discard lines that
do not start with "You " very fast. The lines that start with "You " will
not be so fast, since we have 4 paths to choose and we have to put the
variable (P1) to the verb (punch/hit/miss/slash) in the parenthesis. Of
course, if this were to be perl (hey Ken!;), we would use "^You
(?:punch|hit|miss|slash) " to avoid the unnecessary variable clogging. But
still, I believe this is the fastest of them all, unless tf's glob matching
is hyper-optimized. Also, as I said, IMHO, whatever, the second way is the
worst way to do it because it requires additional matching and the speed
gain achieved by preliminary narrowing of the matches is very slim.

