Phew, I think I got it. So you have a lot of cleric spells
("sanc","whatever") and a lot of mage spells ("sandstorm","thingy") and you
want to use some kind of a construct to do /cast sandstorm and /cast sanc
so that it casts them appropriately. And you want to be able to just type
/cast san and have it pick the first cleric spell starting with san or if
there isn't one, the first mage spell starting with san. [ If you meant
just that we should pick alphabetically the next spell name after "san",
which is "sanc" not "sandstorm", ignore the talk later about 2 separate
lists. ]


There's a lot of solutions for this, some harder than others.

First of all, you could use some kind of variable stuff (/set
spell_sanc=cleric%;/set spell_sandstorm=mage, etc), but I think that isn't
the best solution.

Secondly, what I would use, is make real macros for every spell, eg.
   /def spell_sanc = /cast_cleric sanc
   /def spell_sandstorm = /cast_mage sandstorm
In which case you can put invidual casting procedures here, too, if you
happen to have some spells which require additional operations or have
special effects. Then I would do the /cast command to do something like
/eval /spell_%1 to do the casts (ofcourse handling multiple parameters).
But now we have the problem of how to handle /cast san. If we were to treat
cleric and mage spells the same, we could just do a /list spell_* and stuff
the command names in to a variable and then use the functions available in
complete.tf to do our stuff for us. If we really really need the cleric
spell preference, we could put 2 separate lists and first try to complete
from the first one and if that fails, complete from the second one.

I think the second option gives a lot of flexibility, because not all
spells have to be casted exactly like a cleric spell or a mage spell and if
a spell needs some ingredients or some ceremony to prepare for them, we can
implement those easily.

I hope I got it right and hopefully I will help somebody else to understand
it too and make a better solution, since there probably is one.

