As long as the '/' is there, you _can_ do that, wherever variable
substitutions are allowed, without an extra /eval.  For example,

  /def execute = /_unique_prefix_%{1} %{-1}

And, even if an /eval were required, you could avoid early evaluation
(and potential security problems) by using the right % depth:

  /def execute = /let args=%{-1}%; /eval /_unique_prefix_%{1} %%{args}

Since you're never going to call the macro directly by hand, you can make
the prefix long and weird to minimize namespace conflicts.

There's no advantage to storing the body in a variable:  it would only move
the namespace conflicts from the macro space to the variable space.

