I'd recommend dispensing with the prompt and using the status line in
visual mode. To do that, put something like this in your ~/.tfrc :

/visual on
/set isize=2
/set cleardone=on

Next, to answer your question:
(this is a modified version of Susan Dittmar's code from an earlier post)

/def -i -F -mregexp -h'PROMPT [|] ([0-9]+)H ([0-9]+)M ([0-9]+)V >' h_prompt
= \
  /set hp=%{P1}%;\
  /set sp=%{P2}%;\
  /set mv=%{P3}

/set status_fields @world:12 hp:6:B :2 sp:4:B :2 mv:5:B :1 @more:8:Br \
  :1 @clock:5 
/set status_var_hp pad(hp,-4,"hp",2)
/set status_var_sp pad(sp,-3,"sp",1)
/set status_var_mv pad(mv,-3,"mv",2)

To add other variables to the status line (eg. spell affects), see /help
status_fields.

Also, if your mud is anything like mine, you will sometime get "broken
prompts" where the prompt is followed immediately by text, which can make
things look ugly and mess up your triggers. To fix that use this:

/def -F -mregexp -t'^[|] ([0-9]+)H ([0-9]+)M ([0-9]+)V >' t_broken_prompt = \
  /trigger -hPROMPT %{P0}%;\
  /substitute %{PR}

In case you do not like/want visual mode, you can use the following in
combination with the above trigger as well:

;set the list of your most important spell affects, this is just an example
;you would have flag variables matching the names, and the names must be
;one word in length
/set spells=haste sanc

/def make_spell_str = \
  /let str=%;\
  /while ({#}) \
    /if /eval /test %{1}%;\
      /then /test str := strcat({str},' ','(',{1},')')%;\
    /endif%;\
  /done%;\
  /return {str}

/def -i -F -mregexp -h'PROMPT [|] ([0-9]+)H ([0-9]+)M ([0-9]+)V >' h_prompt
= \
  /set hp=%{P1}%;\
  /set sp=%{P2}%;\
  /set mv=%{P3}%;\
  /let str=$[substr({P0},0,-1)]%;\
  /let aux=$[make_spell_str {spells}]%;\
  /test str := strcat({str},{aux},'>')%;\
  /prompt %{str}

>2.) sometimes i just want to repeat the last command i entered in the
>mud with a trigger.
>an example: i want to disarm a trap, but i fail.
>You miserably fail in disarming the trap. -> then i want to repeat with
>a trigger the last disarm command: disarm trap , disarm rock or disarm
>web or so ... anyone got an idea ?

Repeating the last command is not a good idea in this case, what if you
switched to a background world, looked at a help file, or whatever right
before the trigger activated. Also in this case the trigger will give you
all the information you need. E.g.:

/def -F -mregexp -t'^You miserably fail in disarming (the |a
)?([A-z]+)[.]$' t_fail_disarm = \
  disarm %{P2}

You may want it to give up if it fails 10 times or whatever. Then you'd use
something like this:

/alias disarm \
  /set disarm_attempts=0%;\
  /send disarm %{*}

/def -F -mregexp -t'^You miserably fail in disarming (the |a
)?([A-z]+)[.]$' t_fail_disarm = \
  /if (disarm_attempts < 10) \
    /send disarm %{P2}%;\
    /test disarm_attempts := disarm_attempts++%;\
  /else \
    /echo The %{P2} does not want to be disarmed it seems! %;\
  /endif

See /help regexp, /help substitution and /help evaluation for more info on
these painful looking characters :-)

