Oliver Tonge wrote: 
> 
> - Is there anyone out there using TF to make calls to a database?
> Im thinking of something like TF seeing lines from a world including a
> description like "adolescent long-haired elf" grabbing that as a regexp
> and getting the player's name from a databse. I guess you could do it
> with grep and a flat fil, but that might be real slow?

Unless you have a large number of data, a heavy-duty database manager
won't be noticably faster than a flat file or TF macro system.  The TF
language is not terribly efficient, but using it would avoid the overhead
of shelling out to access a database manager or grep a file.  There are
at least a couple different ways of implementing a database table in tf:

* Make each db entry a variable, like this:

  /set Bob_desc=You see an adolescent long-haired elf.

  Then you can get a list of variables that match "adolescent long-haired elf"
  like this:

  /listvar -mregexp -s _desc$$ adolescent long-haired elf

  This method can be extended to other "columns" by choosing appropriate
  variable names, like <name>_age, <name>_hp, <name>_is_hostile.
  One problem with this method is that <name> must fit within TF's variable
  naming restrictions (but this can be overcome by encoding <name>).
  You could also use macros instead of variables; macro names have fewer
  restrictions.

* Create a bogus world, and make each db row a macro that sets variables
  for each column, and use the primary index as a trigger in the bogus
  world.  Here's a stripped-down example from a recent project of mine:

  /addworld calendar bogus bogus
  /def -p10 -mregexp -wcalendar -t"^[Nn]ew +[Yy]ear'?s +[Ee]ve$$" = \
      /test description:="New Year's Eve", month:=12, day:=31
  /def -p1 -wcalendar -t"*" = \
      /test description:="Unknown day", month:=0, day:=0

  Then you can search on the primary key like this:

  /trigger -wcalendar new years eve

  and the variables description, month, and day will be set appropriately.
  The biggest disadvantage of this method is that you can search ONLY on
  the primary key.  Also, the position of the regexp is reversed:  the
  searcher gives only a simple string, and the primary key regexp has to
  anticipate all possible spellings the searcher might use.

> - Anyone done any work integrating TF and another programming
> environment (eg Prolog) , for NL parsing of stuff from a world? Im
> particularly interested in black-box/nueral network type approaches to
> this... 

TF's triggers can be used like rules of a production system, using
trigger priority to define the conflict resolution strategy.  The
second db example above shows how you might start such a system; each
trigger could continue the chain by calling /trigger again (maybe into a
different rule set (bogus world)).  The details are left as an exercise
for the reader. :)

> - Does anyone use TF for system admin tools?

I've used TF to upload config files to a Gauntlet firewall, and
occasionally taken advantage of TF's features to quickly write scripts
in TF that would've taken more work in /bin/sh (maybe I could've used
perl, but I know TF better than perl).

