In 40a7, "/echo -w<world>" was fixed, but "/echo -w" (with no "<world>")
was still broken (in a different way).

This problem does indeed involve getopts().  (It could be argued that
the real problem is that the argument to -w was optional, violating the
traditional unix rules for options, but we're stuck with that now).  It
will be fixed in the next release, but for now, here's a version of
/echo that doesn't have the problem:

/def -i echo = \
    /let opt_a=%; \
    /let opt_w=()%; \
    /let opt_p=0%; /let opt_o=0%; /let opt_e=0%; /let opt_r=0%; \
    /if (!getopts("a:poerw:")) /return 0%; /endif%; \
    /return echo({*}, opt_a, !!opt_p, \
        (opt_w !~ "()") ? strcat("w",opt_w) : opt_e ? "e" : opt_r ? "r" : "o")

(I chose "()" because it is not a legal world name.)

