> something easy to remedy?

TF deals with two kinds of display attributes:  "simple" (bold, underline,
reverse, flash, dim) and color.  TF gets the codes for the simple
attributes from your system's termcap (or terminfo) datbase, according to
the value of the %{TERM} variable; so it is important that you have %{TERM}
set correctly.  Because most termcaps don't include color codes, TF gets
those codes from the %{start_color_*} and %{end_color} variables.

TF uses these codes when it needs to display an attribute (in internal
form) on your terminal.  %{TERM} determines how simple attributes are
displayed, and %{start_color_*} determines how colors are displayed.

If your terminal does not support the simple attribute codes defined in
termcap (eg, you see mangled codes instead of underline/reverse/bold on
your screen), then either your system's termcap database is buggy, or
you're using the wrong value for %{TERM}.  I think this is the problem
you are having.

If your terminal does not support ANSI color codes, you should set the
start_color_* variables to codes that are supported by your terminal, or
unset them.  For example, add this to your .tfrc:

  /if (TERM =~ "ADM3e-br") \
      /quote -S /unset `/listvar -s start_color_*%; \
      /unset end_color%; \
  /endif

Note that some terminals display simple attributes (as defined by their
termcap entry) in color.  For example, sending a vt100 underline code to
some DOS vt100 emulators will produce magenta text.  As far as TF is
concerned, that is underline, not magenta, and the terminal emulator is
wrong.  I have no idea what an ADM3e-br does.

The default %{status_fields} does not contain color attributes, only simple
attributes.

