Works yes, "the way it should be" no :)

What we want to match is a word-boundary [Rr]ed and a word-boundary. Word
boundary is (as defined by the perl regular expression man page) is a spot
between two characters that has a word character on one side of it and a
non-word character on the other side of it (in either order), counting the
imaginary characters off the beginning and end of the string as matching a
non-word character.

What indeed is a word character is defined by the current locale. The
POSIX definition is alphanumeric and "_".

So, in perl, the language of heavens, the expression would be
m/\b[Rr]ed\b/;

And how it should be done in tf:

Since we have no direct locale accessing in tf, we have to elaborate a bit
on the word character issue. We can take the specific approach by defining
word characters as [A-Za-z0-9_]. To this we have to add the language
specific characters as '', '' or ''. Or we could say that all character
but some delimiting characters are word characters [^()[]{}<>!?. -].

I personally am in favor of the first alternative.

Also, we can not do the simple things as matching the space between
something or do zero-width positive lookahead assertions with tinyfugue's
limited regular expression syntax, so we have to confine ourselves to
matching just non-word character, red, non-word character.

So, if you ask me, I would put this as:
/def -F -mregexp -P2BCred -t'([^A-Za-z0-9_]|^)([Rr]ed)([^A-Za-z0-9_]|$)'
red_lite

