> 
> Why handle the prompting at all ?

Telnet just dumps everything the screen, without caring what any of it
means.  TF does much more: separates input from output so they don't
clobber each other (in visual or non-visual mode), triggers on and
hilites incoming lines, stores lines in history where they can be
/recall'ed, etc.  For all these reasons and more, TF needs to know the
difference between a normal line and a prompt.

Most muds use unterminated prompts, which are indistinguishable from
incomplete normal lines.  These are incompatible with the way TF works,
but TF does a pretty good job of handling them correctly anyway if
lp=on and prompt_sec and prompt_usec are set to reasonable values
(the default values are usually good; both 0 is very bad).

If your mud supports the protocol described in "/help prompts", you can
avoid prompting problems by using it.  If it's not supported, ask your
mud administrators to add it.

All this said, prompt handling is only one possible cause of your color
problem.  There are also a great number of buggy terminal emulators out
there.  Just because "bleeding" occurs in TF and not in telnet does not
mean the bug is not in the emulator; TF does more complicated things with
the emulator than telnet does, and can easily uncover an emulator bug that
telnet would not.

In any case, I have not been able to duplicate any "bleeding" problem.
Prompt timing is impossible to duplicate, and I do not have your terminal
