My solution to this problem may not be the most elegant, or even reasonable by
most folks' standards. However, I have a small file called ping.tf:

--- ping.tf ---- cut here ----------------------------------------------------
/def -w ping = /send think %; /repeat -w -0:05 1 /ping

/repeat -w -0:05 1 /ping
---------------- cut here ----------------------------------------------------

When you /addworld, if you specify a filename at the end of the line, it'll
load those babies up when connecting. For example:

/addworld mymux Geoff Fakeword hair.net 3456 ping.tf

In my example above, 'ping' has been defined with the -w option so that each
world has a separate loop running. A more universal solution is likely
desirable, but the implementation would be more complicated, and it wouldn't
allow you an easy means of refraining from sending to one or more worlds ...
TF's micro-processes don't seem to have terribly sophisticated IPC facilities,
though, so I'm not entirely sure how (short of brute-force scanning the output
of /ps) you could ascertain whether a macro was running or not.

