I think if I were to code something like that, I would detect to see if 
%{fg_world} existed and was not empty - as when you're connected to any world,
you're always going to have that set. 

So, when you start up tf, define something like the following:
 /def idler = /if (fg_world =~ "") %; /then \
   /send -W <your choice of string here %; \
   /endif %; \
   /repeat -0:<your time interval here> 1 /idler %; \

Yeah, it'll keep running when you've got no worlds open, but you won't get any
of the 'send: Not connected' messages this way =)

