> what advantages does tf in win95 give you over the unix version. can you
> have tf triggers in win95 do things on your system could you imagine
> linking wave files to triggers?

Win95 TF has several _disadvantages_ over unix TF, including:

* Scrolling in visual mode is jumpy. 
* /quote ! (and code that calls it, like /sys) is not supported. 
* Compressed files are not supported. 
* Nonblocking hostname resolution (%gethostbyname) is not supported. 

The only real advantages to win95 TF are those you get from running TF
locally, assuming your unix account is remote (or you don't have a unix
account), and you run win95 locally.  Of course, running unix locally
with unix TF will give you the advantages of both unix TF and local
execution.

Running TF locally (especially if your net connection is a modem) will
eliminate typing lag, especially when you're downloading over the link
simultaneously.

Another advantage of running locally (whether in unix, os/2, win95, or
whatever) is that you can have your TF run programs (like audio players)
on your local machine that don't make sense to run remotely.  However,
since /quote ! is not supported in the win95 version, this ability is
somewhat limited in win95.

