CD wrote: 
> how about allowing multiple worlds in /def -w, eg "/def -w'aha,mr,bond'", or
> would the comma be considered part of the world name? (some other
> separator could be used). whatever, just a thought.

There are at least two ways to do this already.

1) Define those worlds with a special type, and use /def -T:

  /addworld -T"tiny.muck.007" aha ...
  /addworld -T"tiny.muck.007" mr ...
  /addworld -T"tiny.muck.007" bond ...
  /def -T"*007*" ...

  The "tiny." part (or whatever you use) will still match the standard
  LOGIN hooks.

2) As of 40a8, you can use /def -E:

  /def -E"${world_name}=~'aha' | ${world_name}=~'mr' ${world_name}=~'bond'" \
     ...

or, assuming you don't have spaces in your world names:

  /def -E"strstr('aha mr bond', ${world_name}) >= 0" ...


I recommend method #1, because it's simpler and more efficient.  For
more complex conditions, use /def -E; it can implement any condition
you want.  All that's required is the expression syntax you already
know and love :) instead of a special /def option for each possible
condition a user might want.

