When I said flash wasn't worth hardcoding, I meant in the TERMCAP
option, for users with deficient termcap/terminfo databases; of
course the flash code would be hardcoded in the HARDCODE option.

Switching from HARDCODE to TERMCAP may in fact have the opposite of the
desired effect on TF's ability to flash:  with HARDCODE, TF would have
the flash code for vt100 hardcoded; but with TERMCAP it very often
would _not_ get the flash code, since many termcap/terminfo databases
do not have that code in their vt100 entries (although I don't know if
that's true or not for the database that comes with the cygwin
termcap).

There is actually no advantage to using termcap in cygwin TF.  The
purpose of termcap is to allow applications to run on any terminal
without knowing the details of every possible terminal.  But cygwin
emulation is vt100 compatible, so vt100 is the only terminal cygwin TF
needs to know, and it already does know about it in HARDCODE.  Making
cygwin TF use termcap would only add to the startup time and size of
the binary and make users download an additional package with its
additional installation complexities, for no improvement.  (This is not
to say that termcap is never useful with cygwin; it IS useful for
porting unix applications that depend on termcap and don't have the
option of using hardcoded vt100 codes.  TF only does so because in 1990
my predecessor felt enough users lacked termcap for the HARDCODE option
to be worth it.  If I had to make the same decision in 1998 I would
probably tell such users to get with the times, but since it's already
in there I might as well leave it there.)

