CD wrote: 

> >> :/ How can I get the return value of a command, eg /listworlds -s or
> >> /listsockets -s without having it echo the result to the screen?
> >>
> >> /def tmp = /listworlds -s %; /let aha=%? %; /echo \%: aha: %aha
> >>
> >> ...puts the return value into %aha but still echos all the worlds to the
> screen.
> >> I also tried piping the /listworlds -s into /return %?, but still no avail :(
> > Piping to /return works, you just have to remember that %| is only evaluated
> > in a macro body, so to do it on the command line you need to /eval.

> I have tried:
> 
> /def tmp = /let aha=/listworlds -s %| /return %? %; /echo \% aha: %?
> /def tmp = /let aha=/listworlds -s %%| /return %? %; /echo \% aha: %?
> 
> The latter gives me an aha value of 1, but I have more worlds :/

They both return 1.  The latter also echoes "aha: 1".  Echoing
is not the same as returning.  Of course, neither is what you want:
it looks more like you're trying to store the string "/listworlds -s"
in the variable "aha" and pipe its 0 lines of output to the next command;
the %? in the next command is the return value 1 of the successful /let.

Both %| and %; separate commands.  With %; the output of the first goes
to tfout (usually the screen) and the input of the second comes from
tfin (usually the keyboard).  But with %| the output of the first goes
into the input of the second.  If the second doesn't actually read input,
%| effectively sends the output of the first to nowhere.  This is a useful
trick when you want to discard the output of the first.  For example:

  /def tmp = /listworlds -s %| /let aha=%? %; /echo \%: aha: %aha

Since /let does not read input, the output of /listworlds is just discarded.

Often it's more clear to move this trick into a simple macro that does
nothing else:

  /def countworlds = /listworlds -s %* %| /return %?

so that you don't have to use the trickery in your main code:

  /def tmp = /countworlds %; /let aha=%? %; /echo \%: aha: %aha

