Multi-line triggers are made one line at a time, eg.

/def -t'first text' = \
	/def -p2 -t'next text' = \
		/def -p2 'third 'text%;\
	/def -F -t'*' = clear triggers

It needs a bit rigging, Ken Keys might implement an expect type system
sometime. But it's doable pretty easily.

Multi line prompts can be handled by triggering the previous line of the
prompt and putting it in a variable and then triggering the second line of
the prompt and displaying both

/def -t'first prompt line' = /set prompt_save=%*
/def -h'HOOK second prompt line > ' = /prompt %prompt_save %*

But remember that tinyfugue doesn't support more than screen width - 1
characters in prompt, eg. tinyfugue can't display multi-line prompts.

You might also pick up all the info you need from the first line of the
prompt and put it into the status line if you like.

