Personally (and as Karen Etheridge already suggested on this list), I
always edit my macros in the file and then /load the file, rather than
edit in tf and then /save.  That way, the file remains nicely formatted
(including comments), and I can organize them by their purpose instead
of having them all in one big file (I have a LOT of macros).

But, if you want to use /save*, you could /def your *FILE macros with -i
so they don't get /save'd or /list'ed.

Another solution is to gag the redef messages.  A simple gag like this:

  /def -agG -hREDEF gag_redef

will gag ALL redefs, which may be undesirable; you may prefer a more
specific gag like this:

  /def -agG -mregexp \
    -h'REDEF macro ^(LOG|MACRO|HILITE|GAG|TRIG|BIND|HOOK|WORLD)FILE$' \
    gag_redef_file

The gag method will also prevent the first set of messages.


