> I'm playing a Chinese MUD with 8-bit codes. I found that sometimes 
> escape key in standard ansi color codes(e.g. ^[[2;37;0m) just 
> dissappeared, it becomes [2;37;0m instead. anyone knows what's going on?

There are several reasons for this kind of behaviour, the most important
being just plain simple lag. Any ANSII code, according to the standard,
has to be transmitted within a certain timespan. So if it doesn't get
transmitted within say 2 seconds, it'll be treated as a normal character
string, and will be sent to your terminal as that same character string.
Since your terminal doesn't know what to do with <ESC>[ codes, it'll just
display it as it gets it.

That's one reason. Another reason could be a slight fault in your xterm
(if you're using that), which basically causes it to print ANSII sequences
that are unknown to the Xterm itself, instead of just gagging them.

I don't know what is your problem, but if you have a very 'stuttery'
connection to the mud you play, it might very well be a lag problem.
(Though I am not entirely sure if TF actually honours the standards
considering ANSII codes..)

