Actually there are a number of solutions to this. Ofcourse none of them
are generally acceptable. Depending on where we are, we can rebind the
numeric keypad to different key sequences which then can be bound in tf.
If we are using a console, we can usually make a new keymap and load it,
to get different bindings for numeric keypad. If we are using X, we can
usually do the rebinding there too... simplest way would be to just use
Xmodmap to redefine those to function keys forexample. A second and more
elaborate option would be to use the xkb extension of some X servers and
redefine the keys there. In there we can really affect the behavior of the
keys and make cool bindings like change only the numlock operation of
those keys. And finally, if we are using Xterm or some other program with
the vt100 widget, we can rebind the keys to (for example) function keys by
using translations... and we can even have it so that pressing F1 changes
between normal numpad and our own version. The xterm receives raw keyboard
events so we can do this. I have F1 bound to switching between normal and
dvorak keymaps and F2 swaps the backspace and delete for emacs.

But, none of these solutions are simple or elegant.

I have devised a new kind of input mode for tinyfugue, which has command
mode and input mode separate, just like vi, so you can bind movement and 
others to the main keyboard and still be able to type. It is however hard
to learn and a bit elaborate, so I wouldn't suggest to anyone but someone
with the utmost need.

