I've got a little function that does something more than that, but also
works pretty well for you :)

It's an adaptation of 'tr' which allows you to change more characters to
another one than just one, or part of a string.

;;; strallsubchr(string change_from, char change_to, string str)

/def strallsubchr = \
    /let old=%;\
    /let new=%;\
    /let left=%;\
    /let right=%;\
    /test old:={1}%;\
    /test new:={2}%;\
    /test right:={-2}%;\
    /while /let i=$[strchr(right, old)]%; /@test i >= 0%; /do \
      /@test left := strcat(left, substr(right, 0, i), new)%;\
      /@test right := substr(right, i + 1)%;\
    /done%;\
    /return strcat(left, right)

Usage is something like: 
strallsubchr(" /.!","_","some/string with/thingies.!")
Resulting in: some_string_with_thingies__

Anyway. It's probably inefficient and all :) But I needed a quick hack to
transform filenames to something that could be used as a variable name.

