> Is there a number of lines where one gets faster than the other or is the
> combined version using (..|..|..) always faster/slower ?

The only real test is to try them all and time them, which I haven't done.
But I can offer some theory.

I'll assume that lines beginning with "[INFO]: " make up a relatively
small fraction of the lines received.  So, the best thing you can do
for performance is to make the other lines get rejected as efficiently
as possible.  Most lines will get rejected before the comparison
reaches the expensive ".*" part.  If you have 3 separate triggers, then
most lines will get tested against "^\[INFO\]: " and rejected 3 times;
if you have 1 trigger with alternation, those lines must only be
tested/rejected once.  So 1 alternation trigger is better.

By the way, in a quoted string (like the -t argument), backslash should only
be used to escape a quote or another backslash.  Thus, to use the regexp
  ^\[INFO\]: (.*) (abc|def|ghi) 
as a trigger, you should write the -t option like this:
  -t'^\\[INFO\\]: (.*) (abc|def|ghi) '

In most cases, including the one above, TF will actually do what you
wanted, but you should not rely on it.  For example, say you wanted to
make a keybinding for
  ^[\
(escape backslash).  If you wrote it like this:
  /def -b'^[\' foo = bar
TF would interpret the backslash as escaping the quote, and it would
continue scanning to the end of the line for the closing quote.  So you
must write it like this:
  /def -b'^[\\' foo = bar

If you /set pedantic=on, TF will warn you about incorrect backslash use
in quoted strings (among other things).

