This excerpt from the next version's "/help functions" should clarify
things:

| Macros and builtin commands can be called using function syntax, unless
| there is a builtin function with the same name. The syntax is
| "name(parm1, ... parmN)". A builtin command called as a function can
| have 0 or 1 arguments; the argument is treated as a command line. For
| example, the function call
| 
|   def("-t'{*} has arrived.' greet = :waves.")
| 
| is the same as the command invocation 
| 
|   /def -t'{*} has arrived.' greet = :waves."
| 
| A macro called as a function can be called with any number of
| arguments; each argument corresponds to a positional parameter (%1, %2,
| etc.). For example, assuming "spam" is a macro, the function call
| 
|   spam("foo", "bar", "baz")
| 
| is the same as the command invocation 
| 
|   /spam foo bar baz
| 
| The function call syntax allows positional parameters to contain
| spaces, which is not possible in the command syntax. (Note: prior to
| version 4.0, a macro called as a function could only take 0 or 1
| arguments, and a single argument was broken into positional parameters
| at whitespace.)

The warning occurs the first time you call a non-invisible (-i) macro using
function syntax with exactly one argument which contains space, e.g.

  spam("foo bar baz")

because that behaves differently now.  Specifically, in 3.x, %1 == "foo",
%2 == "bar", and %3 == "baz"; but in 4.0, %1 == "foo bar baz".  The
warning occurs the first time to inform people who didn't read the new
/help carefully that their old macros may be broken.  However, a
warning for every occurance of such code would be annoying, since it is
still valid code (maybe you really want %1 == "foo bar baz").  Invisible
macros are ignored so that warnings are not generated in standard TFLIBDIR
code not controlled by the user.

The meaning of spam() with 0 arguments and spam("foo") with 1 single-word
argument has not changed, so they do not generate warnings.  The call
spam("foo bar", "baz") was not valid in 3.x, so again no warning for
unexpected behavior is needed (in 4.0, %1 == "foo bar", and %2 == "baz").

