Use PGP and pipe 'world.tf' through it when you start TinyFugue, then have
it reencrypt when you exit TinyFugue.  Invoke TinyFugue through some
script like this:

pgpv -o world.tf world.tf.pgp
tf
pgpe -o world.tf.pgp world.tf

Oh, you'll likely have to dink with it.  You'll have to set up the default
key, you should be sure that 'world.tf' is 'user only read-write'.  You
might need to set up absolute directories.  If you want to get really
grim, you could even set up a shell to do this 'on-the-fly' to have it
decrypt the info only as it needs it, and somehow perhaps not have it hit
the hard drive unencrypted.

In my case, I encrypt logs I archive to zip disk, but that's about it.  If
you are using Win95 which has no enduser security, or if you are using a
public server where your files are exposed and there's nothing you can do,
you might consider installing Linux if possible, even if you are using the
computer from a remote location.  I've telnetted into my own computer at
home from the public library and run TinyFugue from there.  It's about as
secure as I'm going to want for what I do.

From the sound of your situation, your TinyFugue passwords would be only
one of your concerns: Your email, your logfiles, your private work would
be just as open.  While an encryption tool such as PGP can _help_, the
best place to start is to reduce your risks of all around exposure.

