I wrote a noddy little pipe program to server sounds from TF.

I use:

/sys tfsound klaxon.wav

with the tfsound script:

#!/bin/sh
echo $1 > /home/mpc/.sounder

You need to create the pipe .sounder (or .execpipe, or whatever), and
the following bit of C for a 'sound server':

#include <sys/time.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>
#include <fcntl.h>

main()
{
    int funix, n, l;
    char line[4096], name[2048];
    fd_set readfds;

    funix = open("/home/mpc/.sounder", O_RDWR);
    if (funix < 0) {
            printf("Cannot create pipe endpoint.\n");
            return -5;
    }
    
        /* Main loop begins here. */
        FD_ZERO(&readfds);


    for (;;) {

                /*
                 * Add the Unix Domain Socket to the list of read
                 * descriptors.
                 */
                FD_SET(funix, &readfds);

		n = select(FD_SETSIZE, &readfds, NULL, NULL, NULL);
                if (n > 0) {
			l = read(funix, name, 2048);
			name[l - 1] = '\0';
			sprintf(line, "cat /home/mpc/mmedia/sounds/%s > /dev/dsp\n", name);
			system(line);
                }

    }
}


The principle: Cheat. Spawn a very fast syncronous call that just
echo's the name of the sound file to the pipe. The server (that you
start before tf in the background), reads from the pipe, and does
the sound generation.

Note: The server is not the most efficient bit of C, nor is it overly
secure. It is a quick hack I threw together to tie sounds to trigger
matching.

Eg, the following macro sounds a kalxon when a new contact is seen,
provided we didn't sound off in the last 60 seconds:

/set ATS_Contact_Sound=Yes
/set ATS_Contact_pid=-1

/def -i -wMFrl -mglob -t`\[WARNING\]--\[New sensor contact (*): Ship\]` ATS_Contact_Alert=\
	/IF (ATS_Contact_Sound =~ "Yes") \
		/set ATS_Contact_Sound=No %; \
		/sys tfsound klaxon.wav %; \
		/repeat -60 1 /set ATS_Contact_Sound=Yes %; \
		/set ATS_Contact_pid=%? %; \
	/ELSE \
		/kill %ATS_Contact_pid %; \
		/repeat -60 1 /set ATS_Contact_Sound=Yes %; \
		/set ATS_Contact_pid=%? %; \
	/ENDIF


