> Let's get to the chopper!
> 
> /def -i example = \
>         /if (getopts("e")) \
>                 /let file=$[strcat(note_dir, "/", tolower({*}))] %; \
>                 /if ({opt_e}) \
>                         /sh -q pico %file %; \
>                         /recall -g -q $[lines() - (visual ? isize + 2 : 0)] \
>                 /endif %; \
>         /else \
>                 /let file=$[strcat(note_dir, "/", tolower({1}))] %; \
>                 /if (tfopen(file, "r") == -1) \
>                         /_echo %% File %{1} not found. %; \
>                 /else \
>                         /echo -ar %% Contents of file %{1}: %; \
>                         /quote -decho -S '%file %; \
>                         /echo -ar %% End of %{1}. %; \
>                 /endif %; \
>         /endif

Firstly, getopts will ALWAYS return 1 here, so the /else block will never
get executed, as it should be. Try it, eg: 

/def blah = /echo $[getopts("e")]

/blah
1
/blah -e
1

Secondly, what is the purpose of that recall line? Executing a shell
command pauses tf processing, so when you come back you'll get a bunch of
scroll from the latest mud output, ending with the last screen, this will
just echo the last screen again. 

Thirdly, you are trying to use quote on a file handle. If you want to use
tfio, use tfread() or /readfile or some such, and /quote will tell you
whether or not it was able to open the file.

So what you want is something like this:

/def -i note = \
  /if (!getopts("e")) /break%; /endif %; \
  /let _file=$[strcat(note_dir, "/", tolower({1}))] %; \
  /if (opt_e) \
    /def -ag -n1 -hRESUME temp_resume_gag %; \
    /sh -q pico %_file %; \
  /else \ 
    /echo -ar %% Contents of file %1: %; \
    /quote -decho -S '%_file %; \
    /echo -ar %% End of %1. %; \
  /endif  

Have fun,

