Since I work on TF just for the fun of it, I sometimes skimp on the parts
that aren't fun, namely thorough testing and documentation.  And, instead
of hassling with multiple development branches, I've always added new
features and fixed old bugs in the same code, so most releases have had
new not-thoroughly-tested code in them.

This has changed.

You may have noticed that since 4.0 beta 1, the releases have contained
only fixes, no new features.  After the last 4.0 alpha, I split tf into
stable and development branches.  So, the 4.0 branch is becoming
increasingly stable, and I plan on making a better-than-beta (I'm still
trying to decide what to call it) release of 4.0 in the not-too-distant
future.  Meanwhile, I'm adding some major new features to the development
branch (tentatively labeled 5.0).

In the past, TF's version numbering, particularly its 'alpha' and 'beta'
status, has not been terribly consistent.  There have been alphas that
were more stable than some betas.  And while IMO most releases have not
been stable enough to go above beta, IMO the same is true of a lot of
so-called 'release' level software out there; I guess some vendors just
have lower standards.

BTW, TF's apparent 'unstable' status hasn't stopped it from being included
in software distributions.  I know for a fact that it's been published on
Red Hat and Debian Linux CDs, and I wouldn't be surprised to see it
elsewhere.

