Not lower standards, just larger organizations.  The difference between
beta and leading-edge (bleeding-edge) production is that beta is shipped
to a limited number of customers who are then given a shortcut around the
usual support organization to report problems and get help.  The
leading-edge production release usually still has a lot of bugs but now a
support organization is involved so the paying customer gets to experience
the wait-in-queue and poor quality of first-level help that most vendors
make available.  Some organizations immediately escalate problems called
in against leading-edge releases, but only if the user describes the
problem in such a way that it becomes obvious that it's associated with
the new release -- new features, for example, auto-escalate. 


I have often referred to these releases as gamma.  Not quite out of beta,
not really ready for production, but you have to get it out the door or
your competitor will kill you!!

Since Ken does this on his own and makes all releases generally available
to anyone and handles all the development as well as all the support,
there's technically no difference between beta and production.  I guess if
we ever start paying for TF things might change but, since it's a labor of
love, I personally don't care what Ken calls it or how he numbers the
relases.

