If you're using a black and white (1 bit) monochrome display, there is no
way you can adjust the colours with software; everything will either be
"black" or "white".  Your only recourse in this situation is to fiddle with
the monitor's brightness and contrast controls (I often turn my brightness
down at night too).

If you have a colour or n-bit monochrome monitor (n>1), you could also
play with the xterm colours you use (assuming you use xterms).  Personally,
I use -fg LightSkyBlue1 -bg black, which is a bit easier on the eyes than
stark black and white.

As for adjusting colours of all text with TF, you can do this:

/def -Fq -p1000 -aC<colour> -mglob -t'*' colour_all

Take a look at /help colour for a listing of what colours you can use.

All this is assuming, of course, that you are using a terminal that supports
colour.  If it does, /help colour should show up in multiple hilites and
colours.



