For those of you who don't know, a solution for N pieces takes pow(2,N) - 1
moves, so 20 pieces would take over 1 million moves (which I estimate would
take about 47 minutes on my machine), and 30 pieces would take over 1
billion moves (a little over a month on my machine, if it had enough
memory).  Assuming you used the /hanoi in the standard hanoi.tf, the
recursion depth would only reach N+2 (i.e., 22 or 32), well under the
default %max_recur value, so TF would never automatically abort it even
though it takes a very long time.

Of course, /hanoi or any other macro can be killed with an interrupt signal
(^C), which always kills any running macros, and gives you the option of
continuing TF, exiting TF, setting borg=off, or killing quote/repeat
processes.

