TF emulates only a subset of vt100/ansi terminal functions (specifically,
display attributes), so it would be incorrect to respond with "DEC-VT100" or
"ANSI".  If it did, servers might decide it's safe to send cursor motion
codes, etc.  I'm considering inventing and using a nonstandard (non RFC
1700) name, "ANSI-ATTR", which means the NVT supports the display attribute
subset of an ANSI terminal (i.e. sequences of ESC, '[', digits and
semicolons, and 'm').

> The advantage of telling the server that it's tinyfugue is then we know
> other things about the client, like that it's okay to use IACGA or
> whatnot.

True, although it's not really the right way to do it.  Maybe I'll make
it send "TINYFUGUE" first, then "ANSI-ATTR".

As far as IAC GA is concerned, it should be safe to send to any client that
supports telnet protocol, which you can identify as soon as the client
answers any telnet option negotiation.  Only TF and a few others will
recognize the IAC GA as a prompt terminator, but any other client that
supports telnet protocol should handle it gracefully.  Or, you could use the
more robust IAC END-OF-RECORD method, which must be negotiated first.

