Well it can freeze at numerous points. Your terminal emulator might freeze
up on ctrl-s, mine does, your connection might freeze up if stty hasn't
got suspend/resume disabled, or it could even freeze the mud side (seen
one mud implement this). And after all this, it could freeze your 'screen'
if you are running tf under that software. Normally ctrl-q restarts, but
your stty settings might vary. And the screen locks up with ctrl-a 's',
and resumes with ctrl-a 'q'. Oh and your screen or terminal emulator might
send ctrl-s and ctrl-q as flowcontrolling by itself, if it's getting too
much data. You can enable this feature in screen by typing ctrl-a 'f'.

The are many places where the problem can be, but don't give up on
