You can't nest %{} (or any other substitution) inside the selector part
of another %{}.  Often you can use /eval to get around this, by nesting
%{} inside %%{}, but that doesn't work in this case because /for does
not inherit the parameters of /trig.  Using /while and /eval instead of
/for will avoid that problem.

/def deftrigs = \
    /let i=0%; \
    /while (++i <= {#}) \
        /eval \
            /def -F -mregexp -t'%%{%{i}}' tr_%{i} = \
                /set var_%{i}=%%{%{i}}%; \
    /done

BTW, "trig" is the name of a standard command, which is I picked another
name.

