This message is meant mainly for Ken, but I'm still sending it to the list
in case someone else is interested.

Tinyfugue has come to many enchancements lately, but one thing which has
stayed the same is that it still uses the same old regular expression
engine. A better regular expression engine would ease many things
considerably.

I will point here some things how they are in tinyfugue and how they are
in perl and other advanced engines:

TF			Perl		Explanation
[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]	\d{4}		match four digits
....?.?.?		.{3,6}		match three to six characters
[A-Za-z0-9_-]		\w		"word" character (locale dependant)
n/a			\b		a word boundary (zero-width)
n/a			(?:...)		expression grouping without
					creating sub variables
n/a			(?i)		case insensitive matching
\([^)]*\)		\(.*?\)		(not exactly the same, the latter
					uses non-greedy matching which is
					_very_ useful)

And some more complex examples for what is possible with regexps:
foo(?=bar)		Foo followed by bar, but not including it in {P0}
foo(?!bar)		Foo _not_ followed by bar
(?<=foo)bar		bar predeceded by foo

These are just small examples of things that are currently very nasty to
do in tf. Also, we can create every possible glob expression thru regexps
(example, "{foo|bar}" == "(?i)\b(foo|bar)\b"). Repetitions other than
?,+,*, assertions and case sensitivity are the biggest problems with
current regexps.

So, the solution: Implement a new regular expression engine. If you want a
new type for them like -meregexp or something that's your decicion.

Most newer generation engines handle some of these things, but the most
complete one I have found is the PCRE Package by Philip Hazel. It is Perl
5.005 compliant and supports all the latest additions, as look-behind
assertions and conditionals. I have personally tested the package and it
worked very well.

I would love to hear your opinions on the matter.

TIA,
