PCRE is portable as far as I know. PCRE is compatible with tf's current
regexps as far as I checked, and PCRE is based directly on perl regular
expression syntax which is based on V8 Regular Expression engine. GNU
regexps are based on POSIX standard, which imho defined different
expectations on solving ambiguity. So PRCE should me more compatible than
GNU. As for licencing, it has no more of a problem than is with the
previous version of regular expressions, they were too under a copyright.

If you are interested in the subject I would suggest reading "Mastering
Regular Expressions" by Jeffrey Friedl.

Assertions and case insensitivity by parts are imho very important parts
of regular expressions. For example it is hard to do this without case
insensitivity "We are here to help, ((?i)if anything)".

But I can make a proper comparison of the two regular expression engines
and correctly answer these questions somewhere in the near future.

