You probably don't want to connect to localhost through the proxy server,
so you should define Scattermud with -p.

> /addworld -T"lpp" Termite scatter xxxxxxxx sorrows.imaginary.com 5050
> /addworld -T"lpp" Scatter scatter xxxxxxxx eclipse.cs.pdx.edu 7680

> /set proxy_host=10.0.0.2
> /undef proxy_command
> /def -i proxy_command = ${world_host} ${world_port}

Your proxy_command explains the lack of foreground and login.  The default
proxy_command uses /trigger -hCONNECT and /trigger -hLOGIN to invoke those
functions, but yours doesn't.

The localecho is also explained by the proxy, although the default
proxy_command would not handle it either.  The proxy server (not the
mud) requests that tf turn localecho off, and tf complies, before the
proxy server even makes the connection to the mud.

This proxy_command should fix all your problems.  It's just the default
proxy_command, modified for your proxy server's syntax, plus a localecho
correction:

  /def -i proxy_command = \
      ${world_host} ${world_port}%; \
      /localecho on%; \
      /trigger -hCONNECT ${world_name}%; \
      /if (login & ${world_character} !~ "" & ${world_login}) \
          /trigger -hLOGIN ${world_name}%; \
      /endif


> /def -iB"up"    = /dokey recallb
> /def -iB"down"  = /dokey recallf

> The only things I have changed from the 3.5a16 version is
> that I've removed /nohilite, and the up/down key bindings used 
> to be:
> 
> /unbind ^[[A
> /unbind ^[[B
> /bind ^[[A = /dokey recallb
> /bind ^[[B = /dokey recallf
> 
> but these bindings don't work in 4.0g2.

TF 4.0 puts the keypad in application mode; on a vt100, this makes the
up arrow key transmit ^[OA instead of ^[[A.  (You can see this if you
type ^V up).  TF does this for agreement with termcap, so that -B"up"
works.

Using the ^[OA code is the "right" thing to do, but some odd emulators
may still transmit ^[[A.  So to cover both cases, you may want to define
identical bindings for ^[[A and ^[OA (like %TFLIBDIR/kbbind.tf does).

