Johan van Selst wrote:
> 
> When receiving lines that are gagged with -ag, my prompt disappears
> but it is not restored untill I receive another prompt. And a new
> prompt is only sent by the mud after I enter a new command (which
> is quite acceptable from the mud). But I don't understand why tf
> removes my prompt in the first place...

I'm assuming these are unterminated prompts detected with the lp=on
heuristics, not with IAC GA, IAC EOR, or PROMPT hooks.  With lp=on,
when tf receives a partial line, it interprets it as a prompt.  Then,
after some delay, if tf receives more text, it decides the prompt and
the new text are both parts of the same long line that was interrupted
by net lag.  So tf deletes the prompt and prepends it to the new text
to make one line.  If that resulting line is gagged, it doesn't matter;
the gag happens after the joining.

OTOH, if the prompt is definitely a prompt (i.e., it was terminated with
IAC GA or IAC EOR, or was matched by a PROMPT hook), tf will not change its
mind like that.  So, you should be able to prevent your problem (and several
others) by making PROMPT hooks for your mud's prompts.

Perhaps in the future tf will put a time limit on the concatenation;
e.g., if the delay between a partial line and some more text is more
than 3s, then tf will consider the prompt "definite" and will not join
it to the following text.

> Also when I'm typing mud commands that are longer than my screenwith,
> the beginning line(s) of the command are redrawn when gagged lines are
> received. As a result these line(s) are shown twice right above
> eachother.

This is the same problem.  When the prompt is deleted, the entire input
buffer shifts to the left, and must be redrawn.

