Since TF processes triggers, macros, etc synchronously, if you had a method
for pausing mid-execution, the entire TF would freeze (e.g. you wouldn't
see any output on screen, wouldn't be able to type anything, etc).  This is
the same effect as executing something with /quote -S.

Therefore, you need to process your commands asynchronously - which means
scheduling events to happen later.  This is exactly what /repeat does...
so, there is no 'nice' way of doing it, other than putting the commands you
want to run after the pause into a macro to keep the length down:

/def do_stuff2=\
  /do_more_stuff... %%;\
  /do_stuff_3 %;\
/def do_stuff_3=... %;\

/do_stuff %;\
/repeat -10 1 /do_stuff



