Answer number 1, read inside the parenthesis. :-)

Answer number 2, a non-determined finite automata is... a strange thing. :-)
Determined finite automatas are one of the most useful and used things in
programming and computer science, whether people realize [they are using it]
or not.

Non-determined finite automata are used mainly (to the extent of my knowledge,
which is not that extensive :) in protocol study, as far as computer science
goes (automata come from mathematics, so all kinds of studies exist outside
CS).

Most tinyfugue programs are, in fact, automata (or can be reduced to one). Not
surprisingly, since a computer itself is an automatum.

So, now, for the explanation... :-) I'll mix informal description with
explanation here. I think it'll be easier to understand this way.

An automatum is a collection (set) of states (let's call it S :) with a
function indicating transitions between them (f(S,W)->S, meaning that giving
the current state c, and an input w, the function returns a new state n; n can
be the same as c). This explanation can be easily expanded or formalized into
all sorts of automata. Let's give a simple example.

Think of a door. It has two states: open and closed. Giving two inputs, "open"
and "close", it has the following transitions:

State: closed. Input: open. New state: open.
State: open. Input: close. New state: closed.

We can also add (or, formally speaking, must add) the following transitions:

State: closed. Input: close. New state: closed.
State: open. Input: open. New state: open.

Or, we could add another state, called "error", and rewrite the transitions
above as:

State: closed. Input: close. New state: error.
State: open. Input: open. New state: error.

We would have to add the transitions for the state "error" then. Or not. That
depends on how formal we want this. It doesn't really matter, unless you are
applying automata theory to study the system.

So, what do I want to do? Well, it should be obvious that tf's triggers will
act as transitions. It might not be as obvious that /repeat will be used to
make "timeouts" as transitions too. The idea is having a list of possible
transitions, and then adding states and assigning transitions between them.
For every non-defined f(s,w), the system will assume f(s,w)=s, and will either
/undef the trigger or code it so that the state won't change.

ALSO, for each transition between two states defined, assign a macro to be
run. This let's the automata "do" things.

Examples of use:

1) I want an idler. I have only one state, called "idle", and one transition,
triggered by the passage of 30 seconds. So, f(idle,30s)=idle (the software
should spare you of writing things like that, of course; drag&drop on a GUI
would be wonderful, but I don't have the time or the tools -- any TCL/TK
hacker around? :). Each time this transition happens, I call the macro
"idler", defined as:

/def idler = /send :looks around.

2) Gimme a break, that idler s*cked! Ok, let's define two states: idle and
nonidle. We have two transitions: 30s timeout and sendhook. So, I'd do
something like this:

New [S]tate
State name: idle
New [S]tate
State name: nonidle
New [T]ransition
Transition name: timeout
Transition type:
[T]imeout trigger
Timeout time (in seconds): 30
New [T]ransition
Transition name: sendhook
Transition type:
[H]ook trigger
Hook type:
[S]end hook
[C]reate transition table
State: idle      Transition: 30(s) timeout trigger
Enter destination state:
(1) idle
Transition macro: <enter>
State: idle      Transition: send hook
Enter destination state:
(1) nonidle
Transition macro: <enter>
State: nonidle   Transition: 30(s) timeout trigger
Enter destination state:
(1) idle
Transition macro: idler
State: nonidle   Transition: send hook
Enter destination state:
(1) nonidle
Transition macro: <enter>

Yup?

3) Ok, that was better. Now, explain to me why do you want a "non-determined"
automata? What's that anyway?

Well, a non-determined automata is one in which there is possibly more than
one valid transition. What I plan to do, specifically, is make use of tf's
"chance" of a trigger happening. For hooks and /repeat it will be a little bit
more complicated, but absolutely managable (and since the C program will write
the tf code, you don't need to worry about it). That's not exactly what a nfa
is, but there is an nfa for it. Also, there will be random selection between
valid triggers, which is what nfa provides for.

So, what could I use it for? Well, let's get back to the example above. We
have one timeout trigger. Let's define instead 10 different 30 seconds timeout
triggers. Each of them executes a different macro (idler1, idler2, etc). So,
when the timeout happens, it will just select at random one of the macros to
run. Like:

/def idler1 = :looks around.
/def idler2 = :plays with his buttons.
/def idler3 = :tries to catch a fly.
etc

Next, instead of making the timeout a 100% chance transition, let's give it
10% chance. So, after each 30 seconds, the system checks which transitions
"happened" (average 1, of course, but more likely either 0 or more than one),
then randomly selects between the remaining ones, if any.

We could even assign a 90% or 95% chance to the sendhook transition from idle
to nonidle, so that sometimes the idle messages would appear even during
normal action.

So?

