I have been very busy and haven't had the time to look into the matter, but
here I will outline some points on why we should use Perl-like regular
expressions rather than POSIX regular expressions. As for compatibility,
portability and copyright matters, everything seems to be fine, but I still
haven't had the time to look into the matter.

1. Non-greedy matches

The classical example of this is the C comment matching, where we try to
use the regular expression
  /\*.*\*/
to match this line
  /* first command */  not comment  /* second comment */
and we ofcourse see that this doesn't work because the .* gobbles up all it
can all the way to the final comment. This could be solved by other mean
probably, but the regexp would look horrible - with perl regexp that have
been in use for years, we simply write
  /\*.*?\*/
to make the .* ungreedy by changing it to .*?. This is a very important
feature in a regular expression matcher and it was the first problem I ever
had with tinyfugue regular expressions.

2. Subgroups

I have very often big regular expressions with multiple parenthesis. I have
to use often more than 20 of them to make my expression exact. This makes
me hard to extract any values I need from the expression because tinyfugue
spits out fields only for the first 9. I often have to first match the
whole expression and then specifically regmatch a less definite match to
get the fields that I need. Perl facilitates this by having "(?:foo)" to be
exactly like "(foo)" but it doesn't spit out a submatch from it. This can
also processing time for we do not need to assign variables for parenthesis
that are used only syntactically.

3. Efficiency

The perl regular expression engine has been specifically engineered for
speed and efficiency. Example, if an expression starts with .*, it is
implicitely anchored to the beginning, which lessens the speed drain on the
expression. Also, one thing which IMHO is very vital for tinyfugue, perl
regular expressions allow us to "study" the string being matched
beforehand, if multiple matches are going to be used on it. This doesn't
matter much to those glob users, but us regexp junkies might have hundreds
of regexp matches for a line - this way, the processing time needed can be
reduced noticeably. Ofcourse we would have to restudy the string everytime
it's changed thru a substitute or something and the feature should be
toggleable. And there are many ways to finetune the regular expressions
faster, like once-only subpatterns (example later).

4. Comments and extended syntax

We can have comments ("(#this is an important place)") in the regular
expressions and we can use the extended syntax, where no whitespace is
interpreted unless it is preceded with the quoting char ("\"). This makes
large regular expressions much readable.

5. Assertions

The POSIX package knows 4 pre-defined assertions. Or 6 if you count ^ and $
in it also. These are word-boundary, non-word boundary (within word),
beginning of word, end of word. Perl regular expressions have unlimited
ways of creating assertions. Most of the time you are using assertions even
though you don't notice it. Assertions are zero-width operators that look
ahead or look behind in the inputstream. Simple ones are ofcourse done
easily without assertions, example:
  foo(?=bar)                  Foo followed by bar, %P0 contains foo
  (foo)bar                    Same thing, %P1 contains foo
The true power starts to manifest itself when we start doing negative
assertions:
  foo(?!bar)                  Foo that is not followed by bar
  (foo)[^b][^a][^r]           but what if the string ends before that?
  (foo)([^b][^a][^r]|.{0,2}$) ...and it even spits out extra fields etc.
But this is all doable, and gets simpler if we move it to tf code. Then we
go into lookbehind:
  (?<=foo)bar                 a bar that has foo following it, %P0 has it
  foo(bar)                    same things, %P1 has it
And ofcourse negative lookbehind is fausible, and doing it without
assertions would be even harder. Now let's take a real world example - we
have a word-boundary operator - now we want a digit-boundary operator. We
make the word boundary operator first with assertions. So it's a non-word
character followed by a word character or word character followed by a
non-word character.
  \W\w|\w\W
Now we notice that we have to handle the beginning of the string and the
ending specially.
  (\W|^)\w|\w(\W|$)
Fine. Now we translate these to assertions so we don't change the input
position.
  ((?<=\W)|^)(?=\w)|(?<=\w)((?=\W)|$)
OK this matches already exactly the same things as \b does, but spits out
extra fields, so
  (?:(?<=\W)|^)(?=\w)|(?<=\w)(?:(?=\W)|$)
OK now we have a functionally exact alternative to \b. But, as a closer
examination reveal, this is still not absolutely the same. This part is a
hard one to explain so I'll take an example. We match the line
  ---foo
against
  \bfob  or  (?:(?<=\W)|^)(?=\w)|(?<=\w)(?:(?=\W)|$)fob
So. We start looking for a match from the beginning of the string, and we
find places that have a non-word character behind them, but not a word
character in front of them, until we come between "-f". There we find a
match and continue trying onwards in the string, where we will find the "f"
and the "o". But as we come to the "b", we have a non-match situation. The
match "\bfob" would end there, but _our_ expression starts backtracking to
see if the other alternative of our main alternation would match (the \W\w
| \w\W alteration - our first case matched so the second case isn't checked
until we find a non-match situation). This is ofcourse very minimal speed
loss but still a notable difference. We solve this by making the expression
once-only subexpression like this:
  (?>(?:(?<=\W)|^)(?=\w)|(?<=\w)(?:(?=\W)|$))
Now we have finally achieved exactly comparable functionality with \b. Our
original goal was to make a digit boundary expression so we make it simply
by changing the character classes:
  (?>(?:(?<=\D)|^)(?=\d)|(?<=\d)(?:(?=\D)|$))

Now I could go on at this for hours, showing you how we can make a line
that is matched case sensitively all the way but for two words in the
middle of the expression and others, but I hope I got the point thru. POSIX
regular expressions aren't in no way sufficient for heavy-duty usage as
tinyfugue requires. Studying, expression inheritent case-insensitivity and
other switches are like made for tinyfugue.

And for the url's on where to find more info:
http://sunland.gsfc.nasa.gov/info/regex/ - for POSIX regexp documentation
ftp://ftp.cus.cam.ac.uk/pub/software/programs/pcre/ - for PCRE package
  (the PCRE package is almost fully compatible with perl 5.005 regular
   expressions and is excellent otherwise also)

