On Mon, Dec 28, 1998 at 10:34:00PM -0500, kairo wrote:
> If there any such function to see if a file exists or not in TF
> I want to do something like /if exists("filenamehere") then blah
> You get the idea.

There isn't, but you can do the same thing:

/def -i file_exists = \
  /result !sys(strcat("test -f ",{1}))

If you are not using UNIX, there might be some other way to test for
existance of a file in the shell, otherwise have the "test" executable
available somewhere. Another way is to use tfio:

/def -i file_exists = \
  /let _F=$[tfopen({1}, "r")]%;\
  /if (_F != -1) \
    /test tfclose(_F)%;\
    /result 1%;\
  /else \
    /result 0%;\
  /endif

This is faster, but it will print an error message from tfopen() on tferr
when the file doesn't exit.

